explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER — This macro is invoked twice in the function; you must know its expansion (does it return early, call other functions, print diagnostics, or compile-out to nothing) to decide if those operations are live or dead. If the macro only expands to e.g. a runtime check and an early return/side-effect, its removal would change behaviour.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName — The single meaningful runtime call of the function. You need its specification or implementation to know what side-effects (writes to *task_id, global state changes, calls to other functions) it produces and whether removing the call would alter program behaviour.

LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE — The constant/macro passed to OS_ObjectIdFindByName can change the call path/semantics inside that function. Its value may determine whether OS_ObjectIdFindByName performs any action for this call, so it must be known to judge liveness of the call.

osal_id_t — The type pointed to by task_id; required to know whether writing to *task_id is meaningful (e.g. size/representation, aliasing, volatile qualification) and thus whether any assignment performed by callee is observable.

OS_printf — Appears in the static call graph (likely from OS_CHECK_POINTER expansion). Printing is an observable side-effect; you must know if OS_printf is invoked (and under what conditions) to judge whether the corresponding code is dead.

OS_INVALID_POINTER and OS_SUCCESS — Representative return-code macros/constants used by pointer checks and object-find functions. You need the set of possible return values and when they are returned to determine if any return-path (and the computations producing those values) is semantically unused.

OS_ObjectIdGetByName and OS_ObjectIdRelease — These are internal callees of OS_ObjectIdFindByName (per the call graph). To determine whether OS_ObjectIdFindByName actually performs observable state changes or only computes a transient result, you may need their implementations/specifications as well.

(Only the minimal symbols needed to assess whether the pointer checks, the object-find call, and any printing/return-code side-effects are observable have been listed. UT_* test-stub symbols are omitted unless you intend to analyze unit-test harness behaviour as part of project behaviour.)
